{"parse":{"title":"California Scene Painting","pageid":56460732,"revid":824182238,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>California Scene Painting</b> is a form of <a href=\"/wiki/Regionalism_(art)\" title=\"Regionalism (art)\">American regionalist</a> art centered on the landscapes, places, and people of California. It flourished from the mid 1920s to the mid 1960s.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History\">History</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=California_Scene_Painting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>During the first two decades of the 20th century, California painting was dominated by a local variant of <a href=\"/wiki/California_Impressionism\" title=\"California Impressionism\">Impressionism</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> By the 1920s, this movement had lost steam as painters came under the influence of modernist genres like <a href=\"/wiki/Cubism\" title=\"Cubism\">Cubism</a> and emerging forms of <a href=\"/wiki/Realism_(arts)\" title=\"Realism (arts)\">Realism</a> such as the <a href=\"/wiki/Ashcan_School\" title=\"Ashcan School\">Ashcan School</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Starting in the mid 1920s, California artists developed a new regionalist form that became known as California scene painting \u2014 a term that originated with Los Angeles art critic <a href=\"/wiki/Arthur_Miller_(disambiguation)\" class=\"mw-disambig\" title=\"Arthur Miller (disambiguation)\">Arthur Miller</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Huffpost_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Huffpost-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> <sup id=\"cite_ref-Hilbert_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hilbert-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> The period from the 1930s to the 1960s is  now known as the golden age of California scene painting. Although admired by critics on both coasts, California scene painting did not sell very well in its own day.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>California scene painters worked in watercolor and oil, depicting the state's landscapes, people, and scenes of everyday life.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hilbert_3-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hilbert-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-IM_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-IM-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Varying widely in style and subject, California scene paintings show the influence of a range of precursor styles, notably <a href=\"/wiki/Impressionism\" title=\"Impressionism\">Impressionism</a> (particularly its local variant, <a href=\"/wiki/California_Impressionism\" title=\"California Impressionism\">California Impressionism</a>), <a href=\"/wiki/Cubism\" title=\"Cubism\">Cubism</a>, and <a href=\"/wiki/Realism_(arts)\" title=\"Realism (arts)\">Realism</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Brown_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Brown-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> There is a tendency to romanticize: California is presented as the home of spectacular mountain and coastal scenery, pastoral agricultural valleys, and dynamic cities and highways.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Huffpost_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Huffpost-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Stern_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Stern-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> \n</p><p>Notable California scene painters include <a href=\"/wiki/Emil_Kosa_Jr.\" title=\"Emil Kosa Jr.\">Emil Kosa Jr.</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Millard_Sheets\" title=\"Millard Sheets\">Millard Sheets</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/Milford_Zornes\" title=\"Milford Zornes\">Milford Zornes</a>, Phil Dike, <a href=\"/wiki/Rex_Brandt\" title=\"Rex Brandt\">Rex Brandt</a>, Phil Paradise, Elsie Palmer Payne, <a href=\"/wiki/Elsie_Lower_Pomeroy\" title=\"Elsie Lower Pomeroy\">Elsie Lower Pomeroy</a>, Barse Miller, Paul Sample, Dong Kingman, and Charles Payzant.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Hilbert_3-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Hilbert-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-IM_4-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-IM-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-Huffpost_2-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Huffpost-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> One group  \u2014 including Sheets, Dike, Brandt, Miller, Zornes, and Kosa, Jr. \u2014 worked in large-scale watercolors.<sup id=\"cite_ref-McClelland_1-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-McClelland-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  \n</p><p>A 2014 exhibition at the Pasadena Museum of Art included many of the best-known California scene painters.<sup id=\"cite_ref-Huffpost_2-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-Huffpost-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=California_Scene_Painting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-McClelland-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-4\"><sup><i><b>e</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-McClelland_1-5\"><sup><i><b>f</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">McClelland, Gordon T. \"The Golden Age of California Scene Painting\". <i>AFAnews</i>, Jan. 29, 2018.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Huffpost-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Huffpost_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Huffpost_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Huffpost_2-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Huffpost_2-3\"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/04/15/california-scene-paintings-from-1930-1960-pasadena-museum-of-california-art_n_3084698.html\">\"California Scene Paintings from 1930 to 1960 on View at Pasadena Museum of California Art\"</a>. <i>Huffpost</i>, April 15, 2013.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Hilbert-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-Hilbert_3-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Hilbert_3-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-Hilbert_3-2\"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.hilbertmuseum.com/california-scene-paintings/\">\"California Scene Paintings\"</a>. Hilbert Museum of California Art.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-IM-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-IM_4-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-IM_4-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.irvinemuseum.org/scenepainting.html\">\"California Scene Paintings: 1920s\u20131970s\"</a>. Irvine Museum website, 2014.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Brown-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Brown_5-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Brown, Michael D. <i>Views from Asian California, 1920\u20131965</i>, 1992.</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-Stern-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-Stern_6-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Stern, Jean, and Molly Siple. <i>California Light: A Century of Landscapes</i>, 2011.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Further_reading\">Further reading</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=California_Scene_Painting&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Further reading\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>McClelland, Gordon T., and Austin D. McClelland  (2013). <i>California Scene Painting</i> (<a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/9781616581084\" title=\"Special:BookSources/9781616581084\">9781616581084</a>)</li></ul>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw1279\nCached time: 20180909233341\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usage: 0.124 seconds\nReal time usage: 0.152 seconds\nPreprocessor visited node count: 481/1000000\nPreprocessor generated node count: 0/1500000\nPost\u2010expand include size: 1402/2097152 bytes\nTemplate argument size: 687/2097152 bytes\nHighest expansion depth: 15/40\nExpensive parser function count: 0/500\nUnstrip recursion depth: 0/20\nUnstrip post\u2010expand size: 4413/5000000 bytes\nNumber of Wikibase entities loaded: 1/400\nLua time usage: 0.029/10.000 seconds\nLua memory usage: 868 KB/50 MB\n-->\n<!--\nTransclusion expansion time report (%,ms,calls,template)\n100.00%  106.551      1 -total\n 35.65%   37.986      1 Template:Reflist\n 34.83%   37.112      1 Template:Authority_control\n 29.36%   31.281      1 Template:ISBN\n 13.12%   13.983      1 Template:Ca